<target_code>
Here is the code of OS_CondVarCreate_Impl:
```c
int32 OS_CondVarCreate_Impl(const OS_object_token_t *token, uint32 options)
{
    int32                              final_status;
    int                                status;
    OS_impl_condvar_internal_record_t *impl;

    final_status = OS_SUCCESS;
    impl         = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_impl_condvar_table, *token);

    /*
    ** create the underlying mutex
    */
    status = pthread_mutex_init(&impl->mut, NULL);
    if (status != 0)
    {
        OS_DEBUG("Error: CondVar mutex could not be created. ID = %lu: %s\n",
                 OS_ObjectIdToInteger(OS_ObjectIdFromToken(token)), strerror(status));
        final_status = OS_ERROR;
    }
    else
    {
        /*
        ** create the condvar
        */
        status = pthread_cond_init(&impl->cv, NULL);
        if (status != 0)
        {
            pthread_mutex_destroy(&impl->mut);

            OS_DEBUG("Error: CondVar could not be created. ID = %lu: %s\n",
                     OS_ObjectIdToInteger(OS_ObjectIdFromToken(token)), strerror(status));
            final_status = OS_ERROR;
        }
    }

    return final_status;
}
```
</target_code>

explanation: I found no uses of the standard library function memcmp anywhere in the presented code or in the related symbol definitions. There are no string comparisons performed with memcmp nor any other apparent comparisons of null-terminated strings using memcmp. The code only calls pthread_mutex_init/pthread_cond_init and strerror (which returns a const char* but is not used in any comparison), and the macros/inline helpers (OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET, OS_ObjectIdFromToken, OS_ObjectIndexFromToken, OS_ObjectIdToInteger, OS_DEBUG) do not invoke memcmp or perform string comparisons. Therefore there are no code fragments that need investigation for MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.14 in the provided code.
